         <abstract>
            <p>In this paper we are concerned with the asymptotic stability of the delay differential equation <tex-math>$x' (t) = A_{0}x(t) + \sum\limits_{k=1}^{n} A_{k}x(t_{\tau_{k}})$</tex-math>, where <tex-math>$A_{0}, A_{k} \in C^{d \times d}$</tex-math> are constants complex matrices, and <tex-math>$x(t_{\tau_{k}}) = (x_{1}(t - \tau_{k1}), x_{2}(t - \tau_{k2}, ..., x_{d}(t - \tau_{kd}))^{T}, \tau_{kl} &gt; 0$</tex-math> stand for n x d constant delays (k = 1, ..., n, l = 1, ..., d). We obtain two criteria for stability through the evaluation of a harmonic function on the boundary of a certain region. We also get similar results for the neutral delay differential equation <tex-math>$x'(t) = Lx(t) + \sum\limits_{i=1}^{m} M_{i}x(t - \tau_{i}) + \sum\limits_{j=1}^{n} N_{j}x'(t - \tau_{j}')$</tex-math>, where L, M<sub>i</sub>, and <tex-math>$N_{j} \in C^{d \times d}$</tex-math> are constant complex matrices and <tex-math>$\tau_{i}, \tau'_{j}} &gt; 0$</tex-math> stands for constant delays (i = 1, ..., m, j = 1, ..., n). Numerical examples on various circumstances are shown to check our results which are more general than those already reported.</p>
          </abstract>
